\plainsection{Preface}

This program has three main parts:

Part One is a selection of definitions and routines from Donald E. Knuth's \TeX\cite{Knuth:tex}.
While \TeX, the program, comprises about 25000 lines of \WEB\ code,
here we will need less than 7500 lines of it.  % 7635 -210 = 7415
But our selection will contain some of the best parts of \TeX\ for
example the beautiful line breaking algorithm.
The routines are taken from \TeX\ with as little modification as possible---except
for translating Knuth's original \WEB\ code to \cweb\ code\cite{MR:webtocweb}\cite{MR:web2w}.

Part Two is about \HINT\ files\cite{MR:format}. To be precise: about reading
short format \HINT\ files. This is the kind of files the \HINT\ viewer expects as
input. From such a file, it reconstructs
\TeX's contribution list by translating the
data structures found in the \HINT\ file into \TeX's
internal data structures.  As shwon in Part One, some data structures, notably paragraphs
nodes, will require substantial processing before moving the results
to the contribution list; for example, paragraph nodes are transformed
into a sequence of lines by using \TeX's line breaking routine.

Part Three consists of routines that display ``the page'',
a data structure produced by \TeX's page builder
(or variations of it), on a computer screen. The core of part three is
written in OpenGL and can be used with slight modifications on a
variety of operating systems.
Further routines let the user manipulate what is shown on the screen;
These routines are highly system dependent. They need to
be rewritten for different operating systems.

